# Message Consolidator Deployment Procedure

This document outlines the steps to build and deploy the application to the VPS environment.

## Prerequisites
- Google Cloud SDK (`gcloud`) configured with the target project.
- Access to the target VPS (`chat-analyzer-vps`).
- `.env` file with correct production credentials.

## Deployment Steps

### 1. Build the Binary Locally
Build the Go binary for the target production environment (Linux/AMD64) on your local machine. This is much faster than building on a low-spec VPS.
```bash
# Ensure CGO is enabled for sqlite3/neon if needed
go mod tidy
CGO_ENABLED=1 GOOS=linux GOARCH=amd64 go build -o message-consolidator-vps .
```

### 2. Transfer Files to VPS
Sync all necessary files, including the pre-built binary and the `Dockerfile.runtime`.
```bash
# Sync files to the project directory
gcloud compute scp .env docker-compose.yml Dockerfile.runtime go.mod go.sum message-consolidator-vps chat-analyzer-vps:~/message-consolidator/ --zone=us-central1-a --project=gemini-enterprise-487906

# Sync static folder (recursive)
gcloud compute scp --recurse static chat-analyzer-vps:~/message-consolidator/ --zone=us-central1-a --project=gemini-enterprise-487906
```

### 3. Restart the Service
Connect to the VPS, swap the Dockerfile to use the pre-built binary, and restart the containers. The `static` directory is mounted as a volume in `docker-compose.yml`, so any updates to the `static` folder on the host are reflected immediately in the container.
```bash
gcloud compute ssh chat-analyzer-vps --zone=us-central1-a --project=gemini-enterprise-487906 --command="cd ~/message-consolidator && cp Dockerfile.runtime Dockerfile && sudo docker-compose down && sudo docker-compose up -d"
```

### 4. Verify Logs
Check the application logs to ensure successful startup.
```bash
gcloud compute ssh chat-analyzer-vps --zone=us-central1-a --project=gemini-enterprise-487906 --command="sudo docker logs message-consolidator_app_1 --tail 50"
```

## Important Notes
- **Static Assets**: The `static/` directory is volume-mounted (`./static:/app/static`). Updates to files in `static/` on the VPS host will be reflected immediately in the running container. You don't need to rebuild the image if only static assets were changed.
- **Environment Variables**: Always verify the `.env` file on the VPS matches the production requirements, especially the Google OAuth credentials and `APP_BASE_URL`.
